              question:
                'How do you size a ThreadPoolExecutor for CPU-bound vs I/O-bound workloads?',
              answer:
                'For **CPU-bound** work, start near the effective CPU quota—roughly `Ncpu` or `Ncpu + 1` threads—because extra runnable threads add context switching and cache contention without adding cores. In containers use the CPUs actually available/throttled, not host core count.\n\nFor **I/O-bound** work, Little’s Law gives a starting point: `threads ≈ cores × target utilization × (1 + wait time / compute time)`. Measure blocked versus compute time; do not copy a magic multiplier. Pool size must also respect downstream concurrency, connection pools, memory per task/thread, and latency SLOs.\n\nAlways use a bounded queue, rejection/backpressure policy, named metrics, and separate bulkhead pools for independent dependencies. Load-test throughput and p99 while varying pool/queue sizes. Virtual threads reduce the cost of blocked threads for thread-per-request I/O, but downstream limits and backpressure are still mandatory.',
