              question: 'Redis returns stale data. How do you handle cache invalidation?',
              answer:
                'In simple terms: cache invalidation is about making sure your cache doesn\'t keep serving old data after the real data has changed - and there are a few standard strategies to handle it.\n\n**Strategies:**\n- **TTL (time-to-live)** - every cached entry automatically expires after some time, acting as a safety net even if you forget to invalidate it manually.\n- **Write-through / write-behind caching** - the cache is updated as part of (or right after) the write path, but this needs to be done carefully to avoid inconsistency during failures.\n- **Cache-aside** (a very common pattern) - update the database first, then delete (invalidate) the cache key, rather than trying to update the cache with the new value directly. Deleting is simpler and safer than trying to keep the cache value perfectly in sync.\n- **Versioned keys, or event-driven invalidation** - useful when you have multiple servers each with their own local cache and need to notify all of them when something changes.\n- Simply **accept eventual consistency** in cases where slightly-stale data for a short window is genuinely fine for the business, and bypass the cache entirely on code paths that require guaranteed up-to-date (strongly consistent) reads.\n\n**For multiple app instances with their own local caches:** you generally need a pub/sub mechanism (a way to broadcast "this changed" messages to every instance) to invalidate everyone\'s local copy, or you should just rely on a single shared cache (like Redis itself) instead of separate local caches per instance.',
