                'In simple terms: if `synchronized` fixes your correctness bug but tanks performance, there are several ways to reduce lock contention without giving up correctness.\n\n- **Narrow your critical sections** - only hold the lock around the absolute minimum code that actually needs protecting, and consider **lock striping** (splitting one big lock into several smaller locks, each guarding a different part of the data, so unrelated operations don\'t block each other).\n- Use **`ReadWriteLock`** or **`StampedLock`** when your workload is read-heavy - these let many readers proceed simultaneously and only block for actual writes.\n- Use **concurrent collections, atomic variables, or `LongAdder`** (a class specifically optimized for high-contention counting, better than `AtomicLong` under heavy concurrent updates).\n- Use a **queue with a single writer** (sometimes called an "actor" style design) - instead of many threads fighting over a lock, they all just hand off work to one dedicated thread that processes it serially.\n- **Partition your data by key**, so each thread only ever touches its own slice of data (this is sometimes called "thread confinement") and never needs to share it with other threads at all.\n- Push the concurrency control down to the **database**, using optimistic concurrency (a version check on update) instead of coordinating in application code.\n- Consider genuinely **lock-free algorithms**, but only with real care - they are notoriously easy to get subtly wrong.\n\n**Before redesigning anything:** actually measure the contention first - for example, using JFR\'s lock profiling - rather than guessing at where the bottleneck is.',
